The scene is laid in Aetolia, a fact which has to be expressly stated to the audience (v. 94 Nam Aetolia haec est), since the conventional locality was Athens. On the stage, which represents a street (v. 795 home plateam) before the house of Hegio (v. 96 Senis qui hic habitat), stand two young prisoners of war (v. 1 Hos quos uidetis stare lzz'c captiuos duos) bound together by heavy chains (v. 113 catenas...mai0res quibus sunt iuncti). One of them, Tyndarus, is supposed to be a man of 24 years (v. 980) ; the other, Philocrates, of about the same age (v. 20). By the convention of the Roman stage the town was supposed to lie on the right side, the harbour on the left side from the spectators. The play begins with a prologue, spoken probably by one of the younger actors (of. Ter. Haut. prol. init).
